function catMouseGame(graph) {
    const n = graph.length;
    const status = [...Array(n)].map(() => [...Array(n)].map(() => Array(3).fill(-1)));
    const queue = [];

    for (let i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
        status[i][i][1] = 2;
        status[i][i][2] = 2;
        queue.push([i, i, 2, 2]);
        queue.push([i, i, 1, 2]);
    }

    while (queue.length) {
        const [pos_m, pos_c, t_type, t_result] = queue.shift();

        for (const prev of t_type === 1 ? graph[pos_m] : graph[pos_c]) {
            if ((t_type === 2 && prev === 0) || (t_result === 2 && status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] !== -1)) continue;
            if (status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] !== -1) continue;
            queue.push([pos_c, prev, 3 - t_type, 3 - t_result]);
            status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] = 3 - t_result;
        }
    }
    return status[1][2][1];
}
```


    1. Initialize a 3D array `status` to track game state, representing the positions of the cat and mouse, and if it's the cat's or mouse's turn (state can also include whether the game has ended and who wins).
2. Fill in the base game state where cat and mouse are in the same position (cat catches the mouse) and push such states to a queue.
3. Perform a breadth-first search on the queue, where we visit each situation based on the current game state and the type of next move. If the cat's turn, don't allow the cat to go to the hole (node 0). If the mouse's turn, ignore mouse moves to a state which the cat wins. If there's a feasible move, update the status array and push it to the queue.
4. At the end, `status[1][2][1]` denotes the result of the game (1 for the mouse escapes, 2 for the cat catches the mouse, otherwise 0 for a draw).

solutionCode.java:
    ```java
import java.util.*;

class Solution {
    public int catMouseGame(int[][] graph) {
        int n = graph.length;
        int[][][] status = new int[n][n][3];
        Queue<Status> queue = new LinkedList<>();

        for (int i = 1; i < n; ++i) {
            Arrays.fill(status[i][i], 2);
            queue.add(new Status(i, i, 2, 2));
            queue.add(new Status(i, i, 1, 2));
        }

        while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
            Status t = queue.poll();
            int pos_m = t.mouse, pos_c = t.cat, t_type = t.type, t_result = t.result;

            for (int prev : t_type == 1 ? graph[pos_m] : graph[pos_c]) {
                if (t_type == 2 && prev == 0 || t_result == 2 && status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] != 0) continue;
                if (status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] != 0) continue;
                queue.add(new Status(pos_c, prev, 3 - t_type, 3 - t_result));
                status[prev][pos_c][3 - t_type] = 3 - t_result;
            }
        }
        return status[1][2][1];
    }

    private class Status {
        int mouse, cat, type, result;
        Status(int mouse, int cat, int type, int result) {
            this.mouse = mouse;
            this.cat = cat;
            this.type = type;
            this.result = result;
        }
    }
}
```


